<br>
The show also had some nice in-game shots, and in fact, the show, I think, definately conveyed just why EQ would be fun and fascinating to play.  They emphasized that is was a very social game, where everyone is roleplaying and killing huuuuge dragons, and they also had some footage froma fan faire, where the people certainly looked like geeks, but happy laughing geeks, not pathetic losers.  <br>
<br>
The woman (liz) who lost her child is obviously very angry and emotionally damaged from it.  She is angry, who can blame her.  <br>
<br>
Basically, it was a segment meant to scare parents (and parents *live* to be scared, hehe) but anyone with an open or curious mind was more likely intrigued by the world of eq and online gaming.  <br>
<br>
I feel sorry for all the kids whose parents saw that segment and then they came up and told them &quot;no more everquest&quot;!!<br>
<br>
